- Goodwork, pal.

733
00:49:11,294 --> 00:49:13,228
You got it.
M-I-G-N-O-N.

734
00:49:13,296 --> 00:49:15,355
You got it?
There you go.

735
00:49:15,431 --> 00:49:18,867
- Thank you so much, Sally.
You gotta love her.
- Where is he?

736
00:49:18,934 --> 00:49:21,698
- Brooklyn.
- Okay, let's, uh--
let's grab a subway.

737
00:49:21,771 --> 00:49:23,705
Wait a minute. Wait. Aren't you
forgetting about something?

738
00:49:23,773 --> 00:49:25,707
- What?
- Wedding rehearsal.
Bachelor party.

739
00:49:25,775 --> 00:49:27,709
- Plenty of time.
Plenty of time. Come on.
- You sure?

740
00:49:27,777 --> 00:49:30,075
- Yes. Gotta go to Brooklyn.
Come on.
- [ Barks ]

741
00:49:33,949 --> 00:49:35,712
[ Gasps ]
Prada!

742
00:49:35,785 --> 00:49:37,719
Oh, my God!

743
00:49:37,787 --> 00:49:41,052
Ooh! Prada!

744
00:49:42,758 --> 00:49:45,056
Ooh, I love this stuff.

745
00:49:45,127 --> 00:49:47,061
- That's $20.
- Twenty bucks?

746
00:49:47,129 --> 00:49:49,563
Eve, that's
a horrific knockoff.

747
00:49:49,632 --> 00:49:52,760
At least my fake says "Prada."
Yours says "Prado."

748
00:49:52,835 --> 00:49:55,395
Yeah? Well,
I say for a dollar,

749
00:49:55,471 --> 00:49:57,405
I can buy a little
Magic Marker and fix that.

750
00:49:57,473 --> 00:49:59,498
I'll take it.
Twenty bucks?

751
00:49:59,575 --> 00:50:01,770
Right back here.
Here you go.

752
00:50:01,844 --> 00:50:05,177
Two buckets of balls for the price
of one at the Chelsea Piers today.

753
00:50:05,247 --> 00:50:07,181
- So where are we going to now?
- I don't know.

754
00:50:07,249 --> 00:50:09,217
- Lady, lady, you're a golfer?
- I feel like I feel something.

755
00:50:09,285 --> 00:50:12,914
- Two for the price of one.
- Right where I'm standing.
Hey! Who are you?

756
00:50:12,988 --> 00:50:18,620
Can you believe that?
Two bucket of-- Whoa!

757
00:50:18,694 --> 00:50:21,925
- Will you help me up, ma'am?
Yeah, yeah, help me up.
- Oh, my God.

758
00:50:21,997 --> 00:50:24,465
- Are you okay?
- Is the ball okay?

759
00:50:24,533 --> 00:50:29,027
- Yeah, the back of the head.
Is that all right?
- Oh, my. Goodness gracious.

760
00:50:29,105 --> 00:50:32,438
- I'm all right.
Can you get the flyers?
- Here you go.

761
00:50:36,779 --> 00:50:39,111
- Taxi!
- Sara!

762
00:50:39,181 --> 00:50:42,014
They should
make pills for this.

763
00:50:52,561 --> 00:50:55,792
He's gotta be here.

764
00:50:55,865 --> 00:50:58,834
He's got to be here.
I can feel it.

765
00:51:17,753 --> 00:51:20,153
- Excuse me. Miss?
- Yeah?

766
00:51:20,222 --> 00:51:23,885
- You're blocking my shot.
- Oh.

767
00:51:25,428 --> 00:51:28,056
Oh. Sorry.

768
00:51:33,402 --> 00:51:37,498
This is Nick Roberts,
ESPN News, New York City.

769
00:51:37,573 --> 00:51:41,202
- Oh!
-[Eve] Do you know
who plays golf?.

770
00:51:41,277 --> 00:51:44,678
Guys who are too fat
to play tennis.

771
00:51:44,747 --> 00:51:46,681
Like that guy.

772
00:51:46,749 --> 00:51:48,683
[Man #1]
Well, this is a special occasion.

773
00:51:48,751 --> 00:51:51,481
After all, how many times in your
life is your son gonna get married?

774
00:51:51,554 --> 00:51:53,488
[Man #2]
Well said.

775
00:51:53,556 --> 00:51:56,116
- You wanna know
why I love this game?
- No. Why?

776
00:51:56,192 --> 00:51:58,126
I'll tell ya.

777
00:51:58,194 --> 00:52:01,721
You can take years off from playing
and still come back strong.

778
00:52:01,797 --> 00:52:04,732
Well, me, I haven't played
in over five years.

779
00:52:04,800 --> 00:52:06,267
You're kidding.

780
00:52:08,871 --> 00:52:10,964
- Ow!
- Ooh!

781
00:52:11,040 --> 00:52:13,133
- Are you all right?
- I'm okay.
- Sorry up there.

782
00:52:13,209 --> 00:52:15,143
- Eve, look out!
- Go.

783
00:52:15,211 --> 00:52:19,978
- Oh!
- Oh, my God, I'm so sorry.
I'm, so sorr-- Are you okay?

784
00:52:20,049 --> 00:52:22,142
[ Sara ] Please say something.
Say something.

785
00:52:22,218 --> 00:52:24,379
[ Eve ]
I think I swallowed a filling.

786
00:52:24,453 --> 00:52:26,921
Thank you for letting us in.
Now, Mr. Mignon,

787
00:52:26,989 --> 00:52:29,924
we have an odd and some what
personal question to ask you.

788
00:52:29,992 --> 00:52:32,483
Mignon.

789
00:52:32,561 --> 00:52:34,722
Mr. Mignon.

790
00:52:34,797 --> 00:52:37,561
Mignon. Like the meat.

791
00:52:37,633 --> 00:52:41,831
Mr. Mignon, a few years ago,
did you live with a girl,
first name Sara?

792
00:52:41,904 --> 00:52:45,067
Attractive, dark hair,
kind of, like, mysterious,
you know, really amazing...

793
00:52:45,140 --> 00:52:48,075
- girl.
- Oui.

794
00:52:48,143 --> 00:52:51,579
- Do you know where we can
locate this individual?
- No, I do not.

795
00:52:51,647 --> 00:52:54,343
- Do you remember her last name?
- No.

796
00:52:54,416 --> 00:52:56,350
Oh, come on. You don't
even remember the last name
of your ex-girlfriend?

797
00:52:56,418 --> 00:52:59,410
- I find that hard to believe.
- You don't understand anything.

798
00:52:59,488 --> 00:53:02,855
She was not my girlfriend.
She was just, uh, a roommate.

799
00:53:02,925 --> 00:53:04,916
She stayed with me
for a very short period of time.

800
00:53:04,994 --> 00:53:07,861
- She was placed with me by--
- A roommate finder's service?

801
00:53:07,930 --> 00:53:11,627
Oui. She stayed with me with
her boyfriend for a few months--

802
00:53:11,700 --> 00:53:14,863
- I don't care about him.
- And then he moved out
very quickly.

803
00:53:14,937 --> 00:53:18,429
And at the end of the year,
she moved out too.

804
00:53:18,507 --> 00:53:20,441
Yeah, but did she
leave anything behind,

805
00:53:20,509 --> 00:53:23,205
maybe with her last name on it,
like a receipt, a bill?

806
00:53:23,279 --> 00:53:25,406
- Like a piece of luggage?
- No. No, no.

807
00:53:25,481 --> 00:53:27,472
Anything would help,
really. Anything.

808
00:53:28,851 --> 00:53:30,842
I remember she sat on me.

809
00:53:33,122 --> 00:53:35,613
She-- She sat on you?

810
00:53:35,691 --> 00:53:39,627
Yes. She sat on me
for a while.

811
00:53:39,695 --> 00:53:42,459
I found her...

812
00:53:42,531 --> 00:53:45,091
inspiring.

813
00:53:45,167 --> 00:53:49,297
I guess that is why I started
painting her in the first place.

814
00:53:49,371 --> 00:53:51,305
Oh. She sat for you.
I'm sorry.

815
00:53:51,373 --> 00:53:54,069
That is what I said.

816
00:53:54,143 --> 00:53:56,634
- That's what he said.
- That's what I said.

817
00:53:56,712 --> 00:53:58,703
Clearly.

818
00:54:02,384 --> 00:54:04,318
Do you happen
to have the painting?

819
00:54:10,392 --> 00:54:13,657
Hey, now you're gonna see
what it's all about.
You know, you see her face.

820
00:54:13,729 --> 00:54:16,220
Okay. Yeah.

821
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:19,900
This is her, yes?

822
00:54:23,205 --> 00:54:25,537
Yeah, sure.
Around the eyes a little.

823
00:54:25,608 --> 00:54:30,102
I mean, I'm definitely getting
the British thing, you know,
with the crown and the scepter.

824
00:54:30,179 --> 00:54:33,444
- Do you have a name for
the roommate finder's service?
- They would have the information.

825
00:54:33,515 --> 00:54:36,109
No, I do not.

826
00:54:36,185 --> 00:54:40,849
But if it helps, I do remember
where the service was located.

827
00:54:40,923 --> 00:54:42,857
- Absolutely!
- Yes! Where? Where?

828
00:54:44,460 --> 00:54:47,395
- Manhattan.
- Where in Manhattan, Mr. Mignon?

829
00:54:47,463 --> 00:54:49,454
On 60thStreet.

830
00:54:49,531 --> 00:54:53,865
- East side or west side?
- It was just next to that--

831
00:54:53,936 --> 00:54:58,396
on the left of that
splendid little patisserie,

832
00:54:58,474 --> 00:54:59,907
Serendipity.

833
00:55:02,077 --> 00:55:03,977
That'sit.

834
00:55:08,717 --> 00:55:11,277
Get-- Get ready.

835
00:55:13,122 --> 00:55:15,647
Happy birthday.
It's on the house.

836
00:55:15,724 --> 00:55:17,658
Thank you.

837
00:55:17,726 --> 00:55:19,626
Thanks.

838
00:55:21,296 --> 00:55:23,230
Oh, I'm a god-awful friend.

839
00:55:23,298 --> 00:55:26,131
- No, you will be if you sing.
- [ Laughs ]

840
00:55:28,070 --> 00:55:30,903
Eve, thanks so much
for coming with me.

841
00:55:30,973 --> 00:55:32,907
You're welcome.

842
00:55:32,975 --> 00:55:36,672
Sara, you know,
it's a wonderful thought.

843
00:55:36,745 --> 00:55:40,943
The idea that all of life,
that every single event
is part of some master plan...

844
00:55:41,016 --> 00:55:44,008
designed to lead us
to our universal soul mate.

845
00:55:44,086 --> 00:55:48,045
But if that's really true,
then what's the point of living?

846
00:55:48,123 --> 00:55:52,025
Or making decisions?
Hell, why should we even
get out of bed in the morning?

847
00:55:52,094 --> 00:55:53,925
For the cake?

848
00:55:53,996 --> 00:55:56,863
No. Not for cake.

849
00:55:56,932 --> 00:55:59,594
So that you make mistakes.

850
00:55:59,668 --> 00:56:02,102
Mistakes like this trip.

851
00:56:02,171 --> 00:56:05,197
And if you're smart enough,
you learn from your mistakes.

852
00:56:05,274 --> 00:56:07,538
You figure it out.
You-You think.

853
00:56:07,609 --> 00:56:12,205
You realize that life
isn't some elaborate stage play
with directions for the actors.

854
00:56:12,281 --> 00:56:14,215
Life's a mess, Sara.

855
00:56:14,283 --> 00:56:17,343
It's-It's
chaos personified.

856
00:56:19,855 --> 00:56:22,619
I have to give it
all up now, don't I?

857
00:56:22,691 --> 00:56:24,625
Sara, you have a fiance who,

858
00:56:24,693 --> 00:56:28,629
despite his weird
Eastern music,

859
00:56:28,697 --> 00:56:32,758
which we hope is
just a phase, let's hope,

860
00:56:32,835 --> 00:56:34,769
loves you
very, very, very much.

861
00:56:34,837 --> 00:56:37,032
It's not giving up.
It's growing up.

862
00:56:39,074 --> 00:56:41,042
[ Sighs ]

863
00:56:42,878 --> 00:56:44,709
Let's get out of here.

864
00:56:46,749 --> 00:56:48,717
Yeah.

865
00:57:04,333 --> 00:57:06,358
- Here's one.
- Ooh, catch it.

866
00:57:15,410 --> 00:57:19,176
- It's a bridal shop.
- Oh, my God. The irony.

867
00:57:19,248 --> 00:57:22,581
- Wait right here.
I'll be right back. Stay here.
- Why?

868
00:57:26,889 --> 00:57:28,823
- Time, please?
- Uh, about 7:30.

869
00:57:28,891 --> 00:57:30,791
Right. Right.

870
00:57:40,936 --> 00:57:43,234
They moved downtown. If we get lucky
with traffic, we can still hit it.

871
00:57:43,305 --> 00:57:45,239
- What time is rehearsal?
- Can't do it.

872
00:57:45,307 --> 00:57:47,241
- Taxi!
- It's over, man.

873
00:57:47,309 --> 00:57:49,709
What?

874
00:57:49,778 --> 00:57:52,372
- What are you talking about?
- How can I ignore that?
"Bless the goddamn bride"?

875
00:57:52,447 --> 00:57:54,745
- What?
- It can't get
any more clearer than this.

876
00:57:54,817 --> 00:57:57,251
I'm not supposed to be doing this.
It's not in the cards.

877
00:57:57,319 --> 00:58:00,755
Hey, it's another
one of your clues, man.
Let's talk about it in the cab...

878
00:58:00,823 --> 00:58:04,350
- on the way over.
- It's not a clue. It's a sign.

879
00:58:04,426 --> 00:58:08,590
- What's the difference?
- A clue is what a detective
uses to find a suspect.

880
00:58:08,664 --> 00:58:12,065
The receipt, the warehouse,
that French guy-- those
are clues. This is a sign.

881
00:58:12,134 --> 00:58:14,068
Me never finding the book,
that's a sign.

882
00:58:14,136 --> 00:58:16,366
Sara never finding the $5.00 bill,
that's a sign.

883
00:58:16,438 --> 00:58:18,998
How could something
not happening be a sign?

884
00:58:19,074 --> 00:58:22,066
Maybe the absence
of signs is a sign.

885
00:58:22,144 --> 00:58:23,577
Isn't it?

886
00:58:23,645 --> 00:58:25,738
That's lucid.

887
00:58:25,814 --> 00:58:28,078
Look, I don't know, man.
Maybe there is no fate.

888
00:58:28,150 --> 00:58:32,416
And if there is,
it's not working for me.

889
00:58:32,487 --> 00:58:35,422
You know, it's not actually supposed
to end this way, by the way.

890
00:58:35,490 --> 00:58:38,254
We're supposed to pull the curtain
and see the wizard, all right?

891
00:58:38,327 --> 00:58:41,091
- Get to the end of the river.
- This is the end of the river.
My wedding rehearsal...

892
00:58:41,163 --> 00:58:43,097
starts in less
than an hour.

893
00:58:43,165 --> 00:58:45,258
- My bride is waiting for me.
- Let me ask you something here.

894
00:58:45,334 --> 00:58:49,270
If Sara were here right now,
poof, came down, what would
she tell you to do?

895
00:58:49,338 --> 00:58:51,602
She would tell me to run,
not walk to the Waldorf...

896
00:58:51,673 --> 00:58:53,937
because all the signs
point to me getting married.

897
00:58:54,009 --> 00:58:55,943
Look. Wedding dress.
Lots of white.

898
00:58:56,011 --> 00:58:58,536
- I hate to state the obvious--
- State it.

899
00:58:58,614 --> 00:59:02,311
If you don't do this,
you may never find out who Sara is.

900
00:59:02,384 --> 00:59:06,115
Maybe I was never
supposed to.

901
00:59:06,188 --> 00:59:08,122
Maybe all this
is just a maze...

902
00:59:08,190 --> 00:59:11,990
designed to lead me directly
back to where I started.

903
00:59:14,696 --> 00:59:16,823
Which is getting married.

